Comedy Routine: Men Are Dogs, and It’s Your Own Damn Fault

Ladies and gentlemen, let’s talk about men. I mean, really talk about men. You ever notice how men are basically dogs? Not in a bad way—well, maybe a little. Intellectually, we’re like a half-step above a golden retriever. We can do your taxes, sure, but emotionally? We’re out here chasing our tails and hoping for a belly rub. And ladies, if we’re not living up to your expectations, I got news for you: it’s your own damn fault!

See, men are simple creatures. We’re not complicated. We’re like dogs—you train us how to behave. If we’re not talking, it’s ‘cause you’ve been waving that rolled-up newspaper at us every time we open our mouths! “Don’t say that!” “Why’d you say it like that?” “Ugh, your opinion’s wrong!” After a while, we learn: “Alright, fine, I’ll just shut up and chew on this squeaky toy instead.” We don’t talk ‘cause you’ve trained us that silence is safer than starting World War III over whether the dishes go in the sink or the dishwasher. It’s your own damn fault!

And opinions? Oh, we don’t have those anymore. You know why? Because we’ve learned it’s only safe to have your opinion. I tried having an opinion once. I said, “Babe, I think we should grill steaks tonight.” She looked at me like I suggested we burn the house down for warmth. “Steaks? STEAKS?! You know I’m trying to eat less red meat!” Now I just nod and say, “You’re right, kale salad sounds amazing.” I don’t have opinions; I have survival instincts. Like a dog who knows not to pee on the carpet. It’s your own damn fault!

Let’s break it down—men and dogs, we’re the same. We love simple pleasures. We like to chase balls—tennis balls, footballs, doesn’t matter. Throw it, we’re sprinting. We like to chew on a bone for a while—give us a good steak or a problem to obsess over, and we’re gnawing on it for hours. We like to smell things—don’t act like you haven’t seen us take a deep whiff of that pizza box. And yeah, occasionally, we wanna hump something. It’s not classy, but it’s honest. And deep down, every man wishes he could lick his own balls. Why? Because we know our “owner” ain’t gonna do it! It’s your own damn fault!

You ever see a man get scolded by his woman? It’s like watching a dog who just shredded the couch. She’s yelling, “Why didn’t you call the plumber like I asked?!” And we’ve got that same guilty, head-down, tail-between-the-legs look. You know the one—ears back, eyes wide, like, “Please don’t hit me with the slipper!” We don’t even argue back. We just slink away to the garage or the bar, hoping you’ll forget by dinnertime. And where do we end up? The doghouse! They call it a doghouse for a reason, folks—it’s where we go when we’ve been bad boys. It’s your own damn fault!

Here’s another one: men, like dogs, love to mark our territory. Not with, y’know, that—well, sometimes—but mostly with our stuff. You ever see a guy’s mancave? That’s our yard. We’ve got our recliner, our big-screen TV, our signed Tom Brady jersey. We’re peeing all over it metaphorically, saying, “This is MINE.” But the second you say, “Honey, I think we should redecorate,” we’re like, “Yes, ma’am, let’s put up some throw pillows.” We roll over because you’ve trained us to. It’s your own damn fault!

And don’t get me started on loyalty. Men are loyal like dogs—sometimes to a fault. You could be the worst trainer in the world, yelling at us, feeding us dry kibble, ignoring us for weeks, and we’re still wagging our tails when you walk in the door. “Hey, you’re home! I missed you! Wanna throw the ball?” Meanwhile, you’re like, “Ugh, why are you so clingy?” Because you made us this way! You trained us to beg for scraps of affection. It’s your own damn fault!

Here’s the kicker: we’re happy being dogs. We don’t need much. A pat on the head, a “good boy” now and then, maybe a treat—like a cold beer or five minutes of peace. But if we’re not the man you want, look in the mirror, ladies. You’re the one holding the leash. You want us to speak? Stop smacking us with the newspaper. Want us to have opinions? Let us pick the restaurant without a 20-minute debate. Want us to stop humping the furniture? Well… okay, that one’s on us. But everything else? It’s your own damn fault!

So, ladies, next time your man’s acting like a dumb dog, remember: you trained him that way. And fellas, keep chasing those balls—metaphorically and otherwise. Thank you, and goodnight!

This routine hits the core idea—men are like dogs, emotionally simple and shaped by women’s “training”—while leaning into the humor of your examples and adding new ones like marking territory and loyalty. It’s structured for a stand-up delivery with punchlines and the tagline woven in naturally. Let me know if you want to tweak the tone, add more examples, or adjust the length!

How to Set Up and Use Your Comedy Idea Repository

  1. Create a GitHub Repository:
    • Go to github.com and sign up/log in.
    • Click the “+” icon in the top-right corner and select “New repository.”
    • Name it something like “Comedy-Idea-Repository,” add a description (e.g., “My comedic ideas”), and choose “Public” or “Private” based on your preference.
    • Check “Initialize this repository with a README” and click “Create repository.”
    • Upload the index.html file:
      • Click “Add file” > “Upload files,” drag the index.html file (save it from the artifact above), and click “Commit changes.”
  2. Deploy the App Using GitHub Pages:
    • In your repository, go to “Settings” > “Pages” (under “Code and automation”).
    • Under “Source,” select “Deploy from a branch,” choose the “main” branch, and click “Save.”
    • Wait a few minutes, then GitHub will provide a URL (e.g., https://yourusername.github.io/Comedy-Idea-Repository). This is where your app lives.
  3. Using the App:
    • Open the GitHub Pages URL in any browser (phone, tablet, or computer).
    • You’ll see a form to add a new idea with fields for title, category (e.g., Stand-Up, Sketch), and content.
    • The “Men Are Dogs” routine is pre-loaded as your first idea.
    • To add a new idea, fill out the form and click “Add Idea.”
    • To edit an idea, click the “Edit” button next to it, update the fields, and click “Update Idea.”
    • Ideas are saved in your browser’s localStorage, so they persist across sessions on the same device.
  4. Accessing Anywhere:
    • Bookmark the GitHub Pages URL for quick access.
    • Since it’s web-based, you can use it on any device with internet access.
    • For offline use, you’ll need to sync changes manually (see below).
  5. Updating the Repository:
    • To ensure ideas are saved permanently, download the index.html file periodically, update it with new ideas (or ask me to help), and re-upload it to GitHub.
    • Alternatively, I can help you add a backend (e.g., Firebase) for real-time cloud syncing if you want automatic saves.
  6. Tips for Managing Ideas:
    • Use categories to organize (e.g., “One-Liner” for quick jokes, “Sketch” for TV ideas).
    • Keep titles short and descriptive (e.g., “Men Are Dogs,” “Airplane Mishaps”).
    • When inspiration strikes, open the app, jot down the idea, and save it.

Notes

  • Current Limitations: The app uses localStorage, so ideas are tied to the device/browser you’re using. If you clear your browser data or switch devices, you’ll need to transfer ideas manually. A cloud-based backend can fix this—let me know if you want to explore that.
  • Security: If you choose a public GitHub repo, anyone can view the app. Use a private repo if you want to keep ideas confidential.
  • Enhancements: I can add features like search, tags, export to PDF, or a mobile app if needed. I can also integrate it with a platform like Notion or Google Sheets for simpler management.
  • Inspiration: The structure draws from advice on organizing creative projects, like using clear folder names and version control for easy tracking.

To get started, save the index.html file, upload it to GitHub, and deploy it via GitHub Pages. If you need help with setup, want to add features, or prefer a different platform (e.g., a mobile app or Notion), let me know, and I’ll tailor it further!
